1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,000
Speaker 1: again naturally.

2
00:00:01,659 --> 00:00:10,179
Speaker 2: And later in the episode, we'll have our calm word tour, where we go over some useful words, idioms and phrasal verbs from today's conversation.

3
00:00:10,820 --> 00:00:16,519
Speaker 1: So while we talk about habits that can change your life, you'll also build your English in a natural way.

4
00:00:16,820 --> 00:00:19,219
Speaker 2: And before we begin, we want to ask

5
00:00:19,219 --> 00:00:25,980
Speaker 1: you something. What is one healthy habit you keep promising yourself, but keep breaking up with?

6
00:00:27,120 --> 00:00:30,059
Speaker 2: That is such a dramatic way to say it.

7
00:00:30,140 --> 00:00:31,199
Speaker 1: But it's true.

8
00:00:31,879 --> 00:00:33,759
Speaker 2: Honestly, sleeping on time.

9
00:00:34,280 --> 00:00:35,179
Speaker 1: Strong answer.

10
00:00:35,979 --> 00:00:37,039
Speaker 2: Embarrassingly strong.

11
00:00:37,939 --> 00:00:41,320
Speaker 1: Mine is saying, I'll just check one thing on my phone.

12
00:00:41,619 --> 00:00:45,240
Speaker 2: Ah, yes. Modern history's least honest sentence.

13
00:00:45,719 --> 00:00:46,179
Speaker 1: Truly.

14
00:00:46,640 --> 00:00:48,240
Speaker 2: Alright, let's get into it.

15
00:00:48,820 --> 00:00:51,979
Speaker 1: Okay, can I start with a slightly uncomfortable truth?

16
00:00:52,880 --> 00:00:57,679
Speaker 2: Depends. Is it one of those truths that sounds wise in the morning and annoying at night?

17
00:00:58,979 --> 00:01:00,799
Speaker 1: Yes, exactly that kind.

18
00:01:01,039 --> 00:01:01,679
Speaker 2: Go on then.

19
00:01:02,159 --> 00:01:05,260
Speaker 1: Most people already know what a healthy habit looks like.

20
00:01:05,480 --> 00:01:07,459
Speaker 2: Yes, that's so true.

21
00:01:08,060 --> 00:01:15,319
Speaker 1: People know sleep matters. People know movement matters. People know stress matters. So usually the problem is not information.

22
00:01:15,799 --> 00:01:22,719
Speaker 2: Right. Nobody hears vegetables are good for you and whispers. This changes everything.

23
00:01:23,519 --> 00:01:24,200
Speaker 1: Exactly.

24
00:01:25,019 --> 00:01:28,180
Speaker 2: The hard part is not knowing. The hard part is living.

25
00:01:28,719 --> 00:01:31,900
Speaker 1: Hmm, real life is where everything gets messy.

26
00:01:32,340 --> 00:01:42,780
Speaker 2: Because real life is weird. You're tired. Your phone is glowing. Your mood is unstable. And suddenly the healthy plan you made at 8 a.m. feels like it was written by another person.

27
00:01:43,980 --> 00:01:46,340
Speaker 1: Morning you is very ambitious.

28
00:01:46,819 --> 00:01:48,299
Speaker 2: Morning me has hope.

29
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:51,040
Speaker 1: Night you has snacks.

30
00:01:51,980 --> 00:01:53,079
Speaker 2: Sadly yes.

31
00:01:53,420 --> 00:02:09,080
Speaker 1: And that's why this first point matters. Healthy habits are not only actions. A lot of the time they're identity choices. Hmm, say more. A habit gets stronger when it stops feeling like a random task and starts feeling like part of who you are.

32
00:02:09,479 --> 00:02:16,520
Speaker 2: Yes, like saying I'm someone who takes care of my body instead of I'm trying to be healthier this week.

33
00:02:17,060 --> 00:02:21,900
Speaker 1: Exactly. The second one feels temporary. The first one feels personal.

34
00:02:22,139 --> 00:02:24,840
Speaker 2: And that's why the word here is intentional.

35
00:02:25,419 --> 00:02:33,340
Speaker 1: Right. If something is intentional you do it on purpose with awareness, not randomly, not just because the day dragged you somewhere.

36
00:02:33,800 --> 00:02:37,939
Speaker 2: And honestly that already feels healthier, even before the habit becomes perfect.

37
00:02:38,240 --> 00:02:43,680
Speaker 1: Because a healthy life is built through small intentional choices that repeat quietly over time.

38
00:02:44,050 --> 00:02:51,099
Speaker 2: So maybe the better question is not what habit should I copy, but what do I want my daily choices to say about me?

39
00:02:51,500 --> 00:02:53,400
Speaker 1: That is such a better place to begin.

40
00:02:53,939 --> 00:02:58,379
Speaker 2: But even when people know who they want to be, there's still another problem.

41
00:02:58,740 --> 00:03:00,240
Speaker 1: Hmm, the environment.

42
00:03:00,659 --> 00:03:04,379
Speaker 2: Yes, your environment is often stronger than your willpower.

43
00:03:04,759 --> 00:03:05,740
Speaker 1: It really is.

44
00:03:05,979 --> 00:03:13,020
Speaker 2: People say why do I keep eating biscuits? While the biscuits are in a clear jar on the counter like confident little villains.

45
00:03:13,939 --> 00:03:19,659
Speaker 1: Or why do I keep checking my phone at night while the phone is literally beside the pillow?

46
00:03:20,580 --> 00:03:20,900
Unknown: A

47
00:03:20,900 --> 00:03:32,639
Speaker 1: toxic bedtime companion. And this matters because people blame themselves too quickly. They say I have no discipline. When sometimes their whole setup is working against them.

48
00:03:32,979 --> 00:03:41,819
Speaker 2: Hmm. Your room matters. Your desk matters. Your kitchen matters. Your notifications matter. What you see first matters.

49
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:47,639
Speaker 1: It's like trying to walk forward while the floor is quietly moving backward.

50
00:03:48,020 --> 00:03:49,819
Speaker 2: Yes, exactly.

51
00:03:50,280 --> 00:04:02,419
Speaker 1: I had this with sleep. I kept saying I wanted to sleep earlier, very serious, very mature. But every night my laptop was open, my phone was charged, and I had no real bedtime routine.

52
00:04:02,960 --> 00:04:07,560
Speaker 2: So basically your environment said no, we're staying awake.

53
00:04:08,099 --> 00:04:08,659
Speaker 1: Exactly.

54
00:04:09,419 --> 00:04:12,060
Speaker 2: And this is where the word detrimental fits.

55
00:04:12,460 --> 00:04:18,560
Speaker 1: Yes, if something is detrimental, it's harmful. It quietly makes things worse for you.

56
00:04:18,899 --> 00:04:24,540
Speaker 2: And sometimes the most detrimental things are not dramatic. They're just always there.

57
00:04:25,040 --> 00:04:30,579
Speaker 1: Constant noise, constant temptation, constant easy distraction. So

58
00:04:30,579 --> 00:04:39,279
Speaker 2: instead of asking why am I so weak, maybe a better question is, what around me keeps making the unhealthy choice easier?

59
00:04:39,740 --> 00:04:42,300
Speaker 1: That question is kinder and smarter.

60
00:04:42,740 --> 00:04:47,000
Speaker 2: Because sometimes the problem is not your character, sometimes it's your setup.

61
00:04:47,500 --> 00:04:51,420
Speaker 1: And once you see that, another truth becomes clearer too.

62
00:04:51,819 --> 00:04:55,000
Speaker 2: A lot of unhealthy habits are not really about pleasure.

63
00:04:55,560 --> 00:04:57,579
Speaker 1: Hmm, they're about comfort.

64
00:04:58,040 --> 00:05:02,579
Speaker 2: Yes, many unhealthy habits are emotional coping tools.

65
00:05:02,899 --> 00:05:04,500
Speaker 1: That point matters a lot.

66
00:05:04,959 --> 00:05:09,980
Speaker 2: Because sometimes people say I'm lazy, when the real story is I'm overwhelmed.

67
00:05:10,360 --> 00:05:11,160
Speaker 1: Or lonely.

68
00:05:11,620 --> 00:05:15,579
Speaker 2: Or mentally tired. Or trying to feel better quickly.

69
00:05:15,959 --> 00:05:26,519
Speaker 1: Exactly, stress eating, doom scrolling, staying up too late, drinking too much coffee. A lot of these habits are emotional before they are practical. They

70
00:05:26,519 --> 00:05:28,160
Speaker 2: give temporary relief.

71
00:05:28,480 --> 00:05:46,279
Speaker 1: Even when tomorrow has to pay for it. Yes. I had a season like that once. I was overworking, under -sleeping, drinking coffee late, answering messages at silly hours and calling it responsibility. Hmm. But really, I was just pushing myself too hard every day.

72
00:05:46,680 --> 00:05:48,779
Speaker 2: You were burning the candle at both ends.

73
00:05:48,779 --> 00:05:56,379
Speaker 1: Right. If you burn the candle at both ends, it means you're doing too much and using too much energy without enough rest.

74
00:05:56,759 --> 00:05:58,079
Speaker 2: It sounds impressive.

75
00:05:58,579 --> 00:06:01,139
Speaker 1: It does. Very adult. Very productive.

76
00:06:02,199 --> 00:06:05,139
Speaker 2: Meanwhile, your nervous system is writing a complaint.

77
00:06:05,899 --> 00:06:06,500
Speaker 1: Exactly.

78
00:06:07,160 --> 00:06:15,980
Speaker 2: And that's why I think the better question is not only how do I stop this habit, but what is this habit doing for me emotionally? Is

79
00:06:15,980 --> 00:06:19,860
Speaker 1: it giving comfort, escape, numbness, relief?

80
00:06:20,519 --> 00:06:20,519
Unknown: Because

81
00:06:20,519 --> 00:06:26,839
Speaker 2: if you remove the habit without understanding the need underneath it, something else often takes its place.

82
00:06:27,220 --> 00:06:30,759
Speaker 1: That's like taking away the umbrella without stopping the rain.

83
00:06:31,160 --> 00:06:33,180
Speaker 2: See? That's why metaphors help.

84
00:06:33,800 --> 00:06:38,160
Speaker 1: They really do. And then there's another layer to all of this.

85
00:06:38,639 --> 00:06:41,600
Speaker 2: Hmm. Modern life itself. Yes,

86
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:45,680
Speaker 1: modern life rewards unhealthy patterns all the time.

87
00:06:46,060 --> 00:06:57,180
Speaker 2: It absolutely does. Sit more, scroll more, sleep less, order faster, reply now, keep going. Do not be still for even five minutes.

88
00:06:57,779 --> 00:07:00,939
Speaker 1: That really is the modern lifestyle speech.

89
00:07:01,360 --> 00:07:07,860
Speaker 2: And that's why people sometimes feel like they're failing privately. When actually, they're fighting something much bigger.

90
00:07:08,279 --> 00:07:15,740
Speaker 1: Because a lot of unhealthy choices are designed to be easy. Convenience is not always on your side. Rest

91
00:07:15,740 --> 00:07:24,240
Speaker 2: takes intention, walking takes intention, cooking takes intention. But distraction? Distraction is already open.

92
00:07:24,720 --> 00:07:28,319
Speaker 1: Yes, the unhealthy option is often the default option.

93
00:07:28,740 --> 00:07:33,420
Speaker 2: Your phone never says, are you sure you want to lose 40 minutes to nonsense?

94
00:07:34,019 --> 00:07:43,579
Speaker 1: No, it says, here are three more things that will steal your attention. Exactly. And this is where cut back on fits really well.

95
00:07:43,980 --> 00:07:50,240
Speaker 2: Right. If you cut back on something, you reduce it. Not necessarily to zero, but to a healthier amount.

96
00:07:50,740 --> 00:07:53,279
Speaker 1: And I like that phrase because it feels realistic.

97
00:07:53,839 --> 00:08:03,519
Speaker 2: Yes. Cut back on scrolling. Cut back on constant noise. Cut back on stress snacking. Cut back on always being available.

98
00:08:04,120 --> 00:08:06,459
Speaker 1: It sounds like adjustment, not punishment.

99
00:08:06,980 --> 00:08:12,079
Speaker 2: Which matters because a habit only works if it fits your actual life.

100
00:08:12,439 --> 00:08:15,939
Speaker 1: Yes, not your fantasy life. Your real one.

101
00:08:16,379 --> 00:08:24,100
Speaker 2: Not the version of you who wakes up glowing has two free hours every morning and somehow enjoys decorating yogurt with seeds.

102
00:08:24,939 --> 00:08:27,519
Speaker 1: A mythical woman. Truly.

103
00:08:27,519 --> 00:08:28,139
Speaker 2: I

104
00:08:28,139 --> 00:08:46,059
Speaker 1: tried one of those perfect routines once. Wake up early, stretch, journal, read, meditate, make a beautiful breakfast. It looked amazing on paper. Dangerous sentence. By day three, I was annoyed, behind schedule, and weirdly angry at oats.

105
00:08:47,779 --> 00:08:51,440
Speaker 2: Angry at oats is such a specific adult crisis.

106
00:08:52,039 --> 00:08:57,220
Speaker 1: It really is. And that's when I realized the routine was not sustainable. Yes,

107
00:08:57,500 --> 00:09:06,019
Speaker 2: if something is sustainable, it means you can actually continue it over time. It fits your energy, your schedule, and your real life.

108
00:09:06,320 --> 00:09:24,019
Speaker 1: That word changed a lot for me. I stopped asking what looks impressive and started asking what can I actually keep doing. That's such a healthier question. Because a routine you quit after five days is less useful than a small one you can keep for five months.

109
00:09:24,019 --> 00:09:31,659
Speaker 2: Yes, a ten minute walk you actually do is better than a one hour workout you keep postponing forever.

110
00:09:32,139 --> 00:09:34,240
Speaker 1: And that's where moderation matters too.

111
00:09:34,740 --> 00:09:38,659
Speaker 2: Right, moderation means balance, not too much, not

112
00:09:38,659 --> 00:09:38,899
Speaker 1: too

113
00:09:38,899 --> 00:09:39,179
Speaker 2: little.

114
00:09:39,559 --> 00:09:44,399
Speaker 1: Which sounds simple, but people struggle with it because dramatic plans feel exciting.

115
00:09:44,879 --> 00:09:48,600
Speaker 2: Humans love saying from tomorrow everything changes.

116
00:09:49,100 --> 00:09:59,500
Speaker 1: And then tomorrow arrives like good luck with that. Exactly. But moderation is quieter. It asks, what is enough? What is realistic?
